  "prompt": "Can Home Depot copy a car key with a chip if I provide them a blank key with a chip?",
  "response": "Home Depot offers key duplication services for a variety of key types, including standard house keys, padlocks, and some automotive keys. However, duplicating car keys that contain transponder chips typically requires specialized equipment and programming that may not be available at all Home Depot locations.\n\nTransponder keys contain electronic components that communicate with your vehicle's immobilizer system to allow the engine to start. Simply copying the physical key may not be sufficient; the electronic chip often needs to be programmed to match your specific vehicle's security system.\n\n**Here\u2019s what you can do:**\n\n1. **Contact Your Local Home Depot:** Reach out to your nearby Home Depot store to inquire whether they offer transponder key duplication services. Services can vary by location, and some stores may have partnerships with specialized locksmiths.\n\n2. **Visit an Automotive Locksmith or Dealership:**\n   - **Automotive Locksmiths:** Many professional locksmiths specialize in automotive keys and have the necessary equipment to duplicate and program transponder keys.\n   - **Car Dealerships:** Your vehicle\u2019s dealership can provide key duplication services tailored to your specific make and model, ensuring proper programming of the transponder chip.\n\n3. **Check with Hardware Stores:** Besides Home Depot, other hardware or auto parts stores (like Lowe\u2019s, Ace Hardware, or AutoZone) may offer key duplication services that include transponder keys.\n\n4. **Mobile Key Services:** Some services can come to your location to duplicate and program your car key, offering added convenience.\n\n**Additional Tips:**\n\n- **Bring Necessary Documentation:** Whether you choose Home Depot, a locksmith, or a dealership, you\u2019ll likely need to provide proof of ownership, such as your vehicle registration and identification.\n  \n- **Cost Considerations:** Transponder key duplication can be more expensive than standard key copying due to the additional programming required. It's a good idea to compare prices and services beforehand.\n\nIn summary, while Home Depot may be able to duplicate some types of car keys, duplicating a key with a transponder chip usually requires specialized services that are more reliably handled by automotive locksmiths or dealerships.",
